{
  "text": "Furthermore, VEGF expression in CRC may be associated with metastasis, recurrence, and poor prognosis [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Therefore, inhibitors of We also reviewed reference lists and discussed search results with experts. Due to its novel nature, abstracts or presentations of any national or international conference on aflibercept were assessed for inclusion. VEGF with high affinity (Kd % 1 pmol/L) and also binds to PlFGs [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Some tumors may become resistant to anti-VEGF therapies because of an increase in the levels of PlGF [CITATION_6] ; therefore, it is feasible that the binding of aflibercept to PlGF could be of interest because by binding or ''trapping'' both VEGF and PlGF aflibercept could possibly overcome the development of resistance to other drugs such as bevacizumab [CITATION_7] . In preclinical studies, aflibercept prevented the growth of micrometastases, caused regression and renormalization of vasculature in existing tumors, and inhibited new vascular growth [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . It is noteworthy that two recent phase 3 trials evaluating the addition of bevacizumab to chemotherapy after first progression in patients with mCRC (Table 4) ",
